CHAPTER 3
EXISTING SYSTEM
In many industrial environments such as construction sites, mines, and chemical plants, worker safety is primarily managed through manual supervision and basic protective equipment like safety helmets, gloves, and masks. Traditional safety helmets are designed mainly to protect workers from physical injuries such as falling objects or impacts. However, these helmets do not provide any capability for monitoring the health condition of workers or detecting environmental hazards.
In the existing system, supervisors depend on periodic inspections and visual monitoring to ensure worker safety. Environmental conditions such as gas leakage, temperature changes, or low oxygen levels are typically monitored using fixed monitoring devices installed at specific locations. These devices cannot always detect hazards occurring near individual workers.
Additionally, there is no real-time system to monitor workers' vital signs such as heart rate, body temperature, or fatigue levels. In case of accidents such as worker falls, unconsciousness, or exposure to harmful gases, it may take time for supervisors or coworkers to notice and respond to the situation.
Because of these limitations, the traditional safety system may lead to delayed emergency response and increased risk of workplace injuries. Therefore, there is a need for an advanced system that can continuously monitor both worker health and environmental conditions in real time, which leads to the development of the Industrial Safety Smart Helmet Monitoring System.

