METHODOLOGY
5.1 NEED FOR EMBEDDED SYSTEMS
The uses of embedded systems are virtually limitless, because every day new products are introduced to the market that utilizes embedded computers in novel ways. In recent years, hardware such as microprocessors, microcontrollers, and FPGA chips has become much cheaper so when implementing a new form of control, it's wiser to just buy the generic chip and write your own custom software for it. Producing a custom-made chip to handle a particular task or set of tasks costs far more time and money. Many embedded computers even come with extensive libraries, so that "writing your own software" becomes a very trivial task indeed. From an implementation viewpoint, there is a major difference between a computer and an embedded system. Embedded systems are often required to provide Real-Time response. The main elements that make embedded systems unique are its reliability and ease in debugging.
5.2 METHODOLOGY
The Smart Helmet Monitoring System is designed to ensure the health and safety of workers in hazardous environments by integrating various sensors with a microcontroller-based communication system. The methodology of the system is divided into several stages including data acquisition, processing, communication, and alert generation.
1.	Sensor Integration and Data Collection: Various sensors are integrated into the helmet to monitor both the worker’s health and the surrounding environment. Sensors such as temperature sensors, heart rate sensors, oxygen level sensors, gas sensors, humidity sensors, and pressure sensors continuously collect real-time data. An accelerometer is also included to detect sudden movements or falls.
2.	Microcontroller Processing: The collected sensor data is transmitted to the ESP32 microcontroller. The ESP32 processes the data and checks whether the measured values exceed predefined safety thresholds. The microcontroller acts as the central unit that manages sensor readings, performs data analysis, and controls communication functions.
3.	Wireless Communication: The ESP32 uses its built-in Wi-Fi and Bluetooth capabilities to transmit the processed data to a monitoring system or cloud platform. Supervisors or safety personnel can monitor worker conditions remotely through a mobile application or web dashboard.
