7.5 COMMUNICATION PROTOCOLS
	The Industrial Safety Smart Helmet Monitoring System uses multiple communication protocols to ensure efficient data transfer between sensors, the ESP32 microcontroller, and the IoT platform. These protocols enable reliable and real-time communication within the system.
The I²C (Inter-Integrated Circuit) protocol is used to interface sensors like MAX30102 and MPU6050 with the ESP32. It allows multiple devices to communicate using only two wires (SDA and SCL), reducing wiring complexity.
The UART (Universal Asynchronous Receiver Transmitter) protocol is used for communication with the GPS module (NEO-6M). It enables serial data transmission between the GPS module and the ESP32 for receiving location information.
Analog and digital communication is used for sensors such as MQ-8 (gas), DHT11 (temperature and humidity), and the noise sensor. These sensors provide input signals that are read and processed by the microcontroller.
For remote communication, the ESP32 uses Wi-Fi to transmit data to the Blynk IoT App, enabling real-time monitoring and alert notifications. Overall, these communication protocols ensure smooth data exchange, efficient system operation, and reliable performance of the smart helmet.
